---
import DocsLayout from '@/layouts/DocsLayout.astro'
---
<DocsLayout
  title="GitLab CI"
  description="Generate a GitLab CI/CD pipeline for building and deploying your app with Shuttle."
  section="ci"
>
  <p>
    Run <code>shuttle ci generate --provider gitlab</code> to generate a
    <code>.gitlab-ci.yml</code> at the project root. The pipeline has two stages:
    <strong>build</strong> (Docker-in-Docker build + GitLab registry push) and
    <strong>deploy</strong> (SSH into the server and call <code>shuttle deploy --skip-build</code>).
  </p>

  <h2>Generate the pipeline</h2>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">shuttle ci generate --provider gitlab

# With options
shuttle ci generate \
  --provider gitlab \
  --branch main \       # trigger branch (default: main)
  --app my-app          # app name (defaults to shuttle.yml app)
</code></pre>
  <p>
    The command writes <code>.gitlab-ci.yml</code> and prints the CI variables you need to
    configure in GitLab's CI/CD settings.
  </p>

  <h2>Generated pipeline</h2>
  <pre><code class="language-yaml">stages:
  - build
  - deploy

variables:
  IMAGE_TAG: $CI_REGISTRY_IMAGE:$CI_COMMIT_SHA
  IMAGE_LATEST: $CI_REGISTRY_IMAGE:latest

build:
  stage: build
  image: docker:24.0.5-cli
  services:
    - docker:24.0.5-dind
  variables:
    DOCKER_HOST: tcp://docker:2376
    DOCKER_TLS_CERTDIR: "/certs"
  before_script:
    - echo "$CI_REGISTRY_PASSWORD" | docker login $CI_REGISTRY -u $CI_REGISTRY_USER --password-stdin
  script:
    - docker pull $IMAGE_LATEST || true
    - docker build --cache-from $IMAGE_LATEST -t $IMAGE_TAG -t $IMAGE_LATEST .
    - docker push $IMAGE_TAG
    - docker push $IMAGE_LATEST
  rules:
    - if: $CI_COMMIT_BRANCH == "main"

deploy:
  stage: deploy
  image: alpine:latest
  before_script:
    - apk add --no-cache openssh-client
    - eval $(ssh-agent -s)
    - echo "$SSH_PRIVATE_KEY" | ssh-add -
    - mkdir -p ~/.ssh &amp;&amp; chmod 700 ~/.ssh
    - echo "$SSH_HOST_KEY" &gt;&gt; ~/.ssh/known_hosts
  script:
    - ssh $DEPLOY_USER@$DEPLOY_HOST "shuttle deploy --skip-build --image $IMAGE_TAG"
  rules:
    - if: $CI_COMMIT_BRANCH == "main"
  environment: production
</code></pre>

  <h2>CI/CD variables to configure</h2>
  <p>
    Add these in <strong>Settings &rarr; CI/CD &rarr; Variables</strong>:
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Variable</th>
        <th>Type</th>
        <th>Description</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><code>SSH_PRIVATE_KEY</code></td>
        <td><strong>File</strong></td>
        <td>SSH private key for connecting to the server. Use type "File" so GitLab writes it to disk; ssh-add expects a file path or stdin.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>SSH_HOST_KEY</code></td>
        <td>Variable</td>
        <td>Server's SSH public key fingerprint (output of <code>ssh-keyscan &lt;host&gt;</code>). Added to <code>known_hosts</code> to prevent host verification prompts.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>DEPLOY_HOST</code></td>
        <td>Variable</td>
        <td>Server IP address or hostname</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>DEPLOY_USER</code></td>
        <td>Variable</td>
        <td>SSH username (e.g., <code>deploy</code>)</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    The <code>CI_REGISTRY_*</code> variables (<code>CI_REGISTRY</code>, <code>CI_REGISTRY_USER</code>,
    <code>CI_REGISTRY_PASSWORD</code>, <code>CI_REGISTRY_IMAGE</code>) are provided automatically
    by GitLab for every project with the Container Registry enabled. No manual configuration needed.
  </p>

  <h2>Getting the SSH host key</h2>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">ssh-keyscan your-server-ip
# Paste the output as the SSH_HOST_KEY variable value
</code></pre>

  <h2>Docker-in-Docker (DinD) notes</h2>
  <p>
    The build stage uses Docker-in-Docker (<code>docker:24.0.5-dind</code> as a service). The
    <code>DOCKER_TLS_CERTDIR: "/certs"</code> variable enables TLS between the DinD daemon and
    the Docker CLI client. This is the recommended secure DinD configuration for GitLab CI.
  </p>
  <p>
    Layer caching is handled via <code>--cache-from $IMAGE_LATEST</code>. The first build on a
    new runner won't have cache; subsequent builds will benefit from the cached layers in
    <code>:latest</code>.
  </p>

  <h2>Environment protection</h2>
  <p>
    The deploy job uses <code>environment: production</code>. In GitLab, you can protect this
    environment (Settings &rarr; CI/CD &rarr; Environments) to require manual approval before
    production deploys, or restrict which branches can deploy to it.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
